                    },
                    "crop169": {
                      "ratio": "16:9",
                      "relativeHorizontalOffset": 0.246,
                      "relativeVerticalOffset": 0.154,
                      "relativeWidth": 0.5846666666666667,
                      "relativeHeight": 0.493,
                      "url": "https://www.thetimes.co.uk/imageserver/image/%2Fmethode%2Ftimes%2Fprod%2Fweb%2Fbin%2F5f802a32-bbb2-11ea-82eb-1588bf47a52f.jpg?crop=877%2C493%2C369%2C154"
                    }
                  },
                  "strapline": null,
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "name": "paragraph",
                      "children": [
                        {
                          "name": "text",
                          "children": [],
                          "attributes": {
                            "value": "Events in Hong Kong brought a peppery response in the Commons. The House held an hour-long discussion about Beijing’s imposition of anti-protest laws in the one-time colony. For Sino-sceptics, this was a chance to say “told you so”. The only people who seemed relaxed about the Hong Kong crackdown, for their own tangled reasons, were a few Scots Nats. One might have expected them to be more sympathetic to a small territory struggling for autonomy."
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "name": "paragraph",
                      "children": [
                        {
                          "name": "text",
                          "children": [],
                          "attributes": {
                            "value": "“We learnt 80 years ago about the appeasement of dictators,” said the former Conservative leader Sir Iain Duncan Smith, long wary of letting China’s Huawei become involved in our telecoms infrastructure. Bob Seely (C, Isle of Wight), another lusty red-basher, told the foreign secretary, Dominic Raab, that “this dreadful law shows China has changed”. Whitehall must stop being naive about the Chinese regime."
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "name": "paragraph",
                      "children": [
                        {
                          "name": "text",
                          "children": [],
                          "attributes": {
                            "value": "Labour usually makes a din about superpowers crushing human rights. Not this time. The shadow foreign secretary, Lisa Nandy, trotted over the jumps but may have been more concerned about her local football club, Wigan Athletic, facing closure. Barry Sheerman (Lab, Huddersfield) compensated for his lacklustre comrades with a hail of princely splutters. “China is a ruthless, communist dictatorship,” he cried, spitting out the words via virtual link from his pillbox in Yorkshire. “It despises democracy. It cannot be appeased. If we do not hit them where it hurts, we will not be able to stop this tiger growing more and more ferocious.” Mr Sheerman was part of a delegation that went to Hong Kong in the 1990s to urge its people to believe that Beijing would stick to its promises on “one country, two systems”. He felt personal anger about what had now happened."
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "name": "image",
                      "attributes": {
                        "display": "primary",
                        "caption": "Chris Patten, the 28th and last governor of colonial Hong Kong, receives the Union Jack flag after it was lowered for the last time",
                        "credits": "Emmanuel Durand/AFP/Getty Images",
                        "url": "https://www.thetimes.co.uk/imageserver/image/%2Fmethode%2Ftimes%2Fprod%2Fweb%2Fbin%2Fee145c46-bbc1-11ea-84a6-a03a9956ea0a.jpg?crop=3600%2C2400%2C0%2C0",
                        "ratio": "1500:1000",
                        "relativeHorizontalOffset": 0,
                        "relativeVerticalOffset": 0,
                        "relativeWidth": 1,
                        "relativeHeight": 0.7789678675754625
                      },
                      "children": []
                    },
                    {
                      "name": "paragraph",
                      "children": [
                        {
                          "name": "text",
                          "children": [],
                          "attributes": {
                            "value": "Tom Tugendhat (C), chairman of the foreign affairs committee, queried the future of British judges in Hong Kong. He possibly referred to Lady Hale, formerly of the Supreme Court, who currently lends her magnificence to Hong Kong’s court of final appeal. Well, “lends” is not quite the verb. She charges."
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "name": "paragraph",
                      "children": [
                        {
                          "name": "text",
                          "children": [],
                          "attributes": {
                            "value": "Even the Lib Dems were fired up. Alistair Carmichael (LD, Orkney and Shetland) said there comes a moment when you must pick a side and the choice here was between the people of Hong Kong and the Chinese Communist Party. That sound in the background? The crunch of open-toed sandals on a military parade ground as Lib Dems joined the colours. There was also some muffled sniggering when Mr Carmichael managed to talk of “the Hong Kong and Shanghai Bonking Corporation”. You wonder what the monitoring bods at the Chinese embassy in Marylebone made of this very British moment."
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "name": "ad",
                      "children": []
                    },
                    {
                      "name": "paragraph",
                      "children": [
                        {
                          "name": "text",
                          "children": [],
                          "attributes": {
                            "value": "Hit them where it hurts: a saying popular with riot-police commanders. Mr Sheerman — who meant it in the sense of trade constraints — was not alone in using it now. Sir Iain felt the West “should hit them in the one place that worries China — its economy”. For the SNP, Alyn Smith (Stirling) gloated that events had been “humiliating” for Mr Raab and “Global Britain”. It may not be long before Chairman Xi is inviting Nicola Sturgeon to a state banquet in the Great Hall of the People. Mr Smith thought the EU had been more active in its diplomacy than London. Mr Raab: “Nonsense.”"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "name": "paragraph",
                      "children": [
                        {
                          "name": "text",
                          "children": [],
                          "attributes": {
                            "value": "The decision to offer a path to British citizenship to three million Hongkongers was announced at PMQs by Boris Johnson. Opposition MPs found themselves in the irritating position of having little room for umbrage. Sir Keir Starmer, Labour leader, instead attacked Mr Johnson for not preventing the Covid flare-up in Leicester. He was cross about some detail of “pillar one and pillar two” health statistics. “That may sound technical,” he conceded. Yes, it did a bit. Captain Constipation, a little enviously, later grumbled about Mr Johnson’s Pollyanna optimism. He said the PM was “flippant”. Mr Johnson: “We are the builders, they are the blockers. We are the doers, they are the ditherers.”"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    }
                  ],
